        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "defined by",
        "bbox": [
          0.20313725490196077,
          0.2381818181818182,
          0.27450980392156865,
          0.25333333333333335
        ],
        "order": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_book_en_5.Advanced.Modern.Algebra.-.J.Rotman.2003_page_887_3",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "is important. Recall that we have seen, in Exercise 8.37 on page 573, that 8 is a surjective ring homomorphism, and so its kernel, G, is a two-sided ideal in ZG, called the augmen- tation ideal. Thus, there is an exact sequence",
        "bbox": [
          0.20313725490196077,
          0.2866666666666667,
          0.7937254901960784,
          0.33151515151515154
        ],
        "order": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_book_en_5.Advanced.Modern.Algebra.-.J.Rotman.2003_page_887_4",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Proposition 10.103. Let G be a group with augmentation ideal G. As an abelian group, G is free abelian with basis G − 1 = {x − 1 : x ∈ G, x ≠ 1}.",
        "bbox": [
          0.20470588235294118,
          0.36787878787878786,
          0.7913725490196079,
          0.3987878787878788
        ],
        "order": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_book_en_5.Advanced.Modern.Algebra.-.J.Rotman.2003_page_887_5",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Proof!. An element u = ∑x mxx ∈ ZG lies in kerε = G if and only if ∑x mx = 0. Therefore, if u ∈ G, then",
        "bbox": [
          0.2023529411764706,
          0.403030303030303,
          0.7913725490196079,
          0.43393939393939396
        ],
        "order": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_book_en_5.Advanced.Modern.Algebra.-.J.Rotman.2003_page_887_6",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Thus, G is generated by the nonzero x − 1 for x ∈ G.",
        "bbox": [
          0.20392156862745098,
          0.4727272727272727,
          0.556078431372549,
          0.48787878787878786
        ],
        "order": 7
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_book_en_5.Advanced.Modern.Algebra.-.J.Rotman.2003_page_887_7",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Suppose that ∑x≠1 nx(x − 1) = 0. Then ∑x≠1 nxx − (∑x≠1 nx)1 = 0 in ZG, which, as an abelian group, is free abelian with basis the elements of G. Hence, nx = 0 for all x ≠ 1. Therefore, the nonzero x − 1 comprise a basis of G. •",
        "bbox": [
          0.20313725490196077,
          0.48787878787878786,
          0.7945098039215687,
          0.5339393939393939
        ],
        "order": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_book_en_5.Advanced.Modern.Algebra.-.J.Rotman.2003_page_887_8",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "We begin by examining homology groups.",
        "bbox": [
          0.2235294117647059,
          0.5381818181818182,
          0.5019607843137255,
          0.553939393939394
        ],
        "order": 9
